Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: sc03 THE BARN NET — v2, crew-hangout rebuild
Draft date: 2026-07-12 09:51

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A hand pulls a cord in the dark and the pull-switch clicks.

A work light swings and steadies over the APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER, hand-machined gauges set in a plywood panel, the numbers inked by hand.

Two seats ride in a welded steel cradle bolted to the barn floor. The couch is an old truck bench, patched at the seams.

A triangular window is cut in the panel. Behind it, painted on the barn wall, hangs a gray Moon the size of a wagon wheel.

ALONG THE BACK WALL -- spiral notebooks stand floor to roof, hundreds of them, every spine dated in the same block hand. The bottom shelf starts in 1972.

CRICKET -- Earl Dawes, 79, seed-cap, a farmer's forearms, settles into the left seat and squares a clipboard on his knee.

He thumbs a switch. A speaker on the shelf pops and hisses.

A relay behind the panel BUZZES, a steady low note.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

The speaker crackles. A dry voice comes up out of it.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Copy nineteen-oh-two. Hold for the count.

Cricket clicks a stopwatch and sets it face-up on the panel.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Apollo Eighteen. Lunar descent rehearsal. Number two thousand, eight hundred and six. Sound off.

CRICKET:
Commander, up.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Systems, up. I want the log to show I said the Bus B relay is due. Been saying it.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Noted for the log, Dutch. Same as last week.

A third speaker, a smaller one clipped to the cradle, opens with a slow Texas drawl already in progress.

STITCH (RADIO):
Backup's up, and listen, before we go anyplace. You boys hear they sold off Ferris Kettle's whole place Saturday.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Stitch. Keep the net clean.

STITCH (RADIO):
I'm keepin' it clean, I'm just tellin' you. Forty-some years he farms that ground and it goes for near nothin' on a Saturday. Fella from two counties over bought the good disc for a hundred dollars.

Cricket runs a pencil down the clipboard without looking up.

CRICKET:
Program's up. Coming to ignition.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Confirm attitude before you light it. I don't want it off a hair like October.

STITCH (RADIO):
A hundred dollars. Man stood right next to me and never blinked.

GUNNY (RADIO):
We are hot for the burn. Ferris Kettle's disc can wait.

STITCH (RADIO):
It has waited. It'll keep waitin'. That's the thing about it.

The buzz holds steady behind the panel. A needle marked ALT swings and settles.

CRICKET:
Ignition. Throttle up.

Cricket eases a lever forward in the cradle. The whole seat trembles on its springs.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Descent rate looks nominal. I've got it logged nominal.

STITCH (RADIO):
Anyway his boy didn't want none of it. Boy's up in Omaha sellin' insurance. Sells insurance to farmers, that's the part that gets me.

GUNNY (RADIO):
We're at high gate. Somebody fly the airplane.

CRICKET:
Forty thousand feet. Coming down.

Dutch's voice sharpens, thin over the speaker.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Hold it. My inverter's reading soft. Cricket, is your Bus B needle steady on your side.

Cricket leans to the panel. The needle marked BUS B sits still, then jumps a hair and falls back.

CRICKET:
Steady. Wait.

The needle wanders down, slow, off the mark. The steady buzz roughens and starts to stutter.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Steady or does it stutter. Tell me which.

CRICKET:
Stutters.

DUTCH (RADIO):
That's the relay. Forty-year-old relay, and I'm allowed to say it, I put it on the log in nineteen eighty-six. Kick it. Low left corner of the panel.

Cricket makes a fist and raps the plywood, low and left, once.

The buzz catches, smooths out. The BUS B needle climbs back and settles on the mark.

STITCH (RADIO):
So I says to his boy, that disc'll outlast your whole insurance company, and he laughs at me.

CRICKET:
Three thousand feet. Rate's good.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Copy three thousand.

Nobody says a word about the relay. Dutch clears his throat and lets it sit.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Log shows Bus B corrected.

STITCH (RADIO):
Y'all want to know what I think, fifty years of Tuesdays, the Moon ain't gonna sneak up on us tonight. It's right where it was.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Keep the net clean, Stitch. Last time.

STITCH (RADIO):
I'll keep it clean when there's somethin' worth cleanin'. Man bought a two-hundred-dollar disc for a hundred and I am gonna sit with that a minute.

Cricket flies on through it, eyes on the gauges, thumb tapping the lever.

CRICKET:
Twelve hundred feet. Pitching over.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Fuel's a little heavy on my board. You've got margin.

CRICKET:
Copy margin. Seven hundred feet.

STITCH (RADIO):
His wife made a casserole for the auction crowd and it was the good kind, the one with the crackers on top.

CRICKET:
Five hundred feet.

The stutter of talk over the speakers thins out. Stitch's voice trails and stops.

CRICKET:
Three hundred feet.

The barn goes quiet. Nobody calls for quiet. The buzz runs on alone under the work light.

CRICKET:
Two hundred. Coming down slow.

Cricket eases the lever back. The cradle groans on its springs and holds.

CRICKET:
Forty feet. Kicking up a little.

A green bulb on the panel snaps on.

CRICKET:
Contact light. Engine stop.

Cricket lets go of the lever. His hand rests flat on his knee.

The buzz cuts out. The barn holds still.

STITCH (RADIO):
You were heavy on that throttle at the end there, Colonel.

CRICKET:
I was.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The man is on the ground, Colonel. Leave him be.

Dutch's dry voice comes up last.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Relay held.

CRICKET:
All right.

Cricket picks up the stopwatch and clicks it dead.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

STITCH (RADIO):
God willing.

Two clicks come over the speaker, sharp and close.

Cricket keys his mike twice. Two clicks answer from Dutch. Two from Stitch.

The speakers hiss, then die when Cricket thumbs the switch.

He opens the top notebook to a fresh page and writes it out in ballpoint block letters, the entry number, then the words bus B corrected, then contact at nineteen forty-one, then crew present by radio.

He stands and runs his thumb down the dated spines along the back wall, from 1972 up to tonight.

AT THE DOOR -- Cricket hangs a padlock through the hasp and pulls it once. It holds.

He reaches up and the work light dies under his hand.

Outside, Cricket crosses the dark yard toward the farmhouse. Every window in it is dark.
